The Security pillar.

Security is the pillar about protecting data and identities against credible threats, and here are the non-negotiables, drawn from modules two and eleven.

On identity, use I-A-M roles, not users, for everything, put permission boundaries on developer roles, and do single sign-on through I-A-M Identity Center rather than local I-A-M users. On least privilege, review I-A-M Access Analyzer findings and size policies to actual usage using CloudTrail-driven generation, never a blanket star-on-star. On data encryption, use K-M-S customer-managed keys for sensitive data, turn on S3 default encryption, enable the E-B-S default-encryption flag per Region, and use T-L-S in transit everywhere. On secrets, use Secrets Manager with rotation, or S-S-M Parameter Store SecureString, and never put plain-text secrets in code, A-M-Is, or Lambda environment variables. On network controls, put compute in private subnets and expose only load balancers publicly, keep security groups tight, and use N-A-C-Ls as a coarse second layer. And on detection, run GuardDuty organisation-wide, aggregate in Security Hub, use Config rules for drift, and keep CloudTrail immutable.

The design principles: a strong identity foundation, traceability, security at all layers, automate security, protect data in transit and at rest, keep people away from data, and prepare for security events. Two ideas recur throughout: defence in depth, layering identity, network, encryption, and detection so one failure isn't fatal, and least privilege, granting the minimum and expanding only on evidence. The cue: encrypt at rest with your own key, restrict the blast radius, or detect unusual activity, all point to this pillar.
